{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"All direct and transitive dependencies are extracted from the manifest and included in the vulnerability check.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise: Unit vs Integration -> Integration wins because failure appears at parser/resolver handoff (manifest reader + dependency graph expansion + check input), not one isolated function. Integration vs System -> Integration wins because this behavior text does not require real network/OS/subprocess; an in-process resolver fixture can reproduce missing-transitive bugs. Rejection gate: rejected System/Agentic/Workflow since behavior only says extraction/inclusion, with no real API call requirement and no AI steps.","test_description":"Wire manifest parser + transitive resolver + vulnerability-check request builder in one test using fixture manifests (with nested transitives). Assert the outgoing dependency set contains every expected direct/transitive package/version and no omissions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The vulnerability database query returns results that match the exact version ranges in the manifest, not just the package name.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise: Unit vs Integration -> Integration wins because failure boundary is between manifest range extraction and query/filter module. Integration vs System -> Integration wins since exact-range correctness can be caught with a stubbed API contract in-process (mixed results for same package across versions). Rejection gate: rejected System because behavior does not require real HTTP behavior; it specifies matching semantics, which can be validated via module wiring and controlled responses.","test_description":"Run scanner query path against a fake vuln API adapter returning CVEs for same package at different version ranges; as